Vaccination Rate and Exemptions in Schools

Jackson Shands

12/14/2021

Project description: This data set contains information from schools about vaccination rates and exemptions (0-100%) along with enrollment and school type. The objective of this research is to investigate the relationship between school type (public or private), enrollment, and the number of medical exemptions granted to students. By developing a linear regression model, the aim is to predict the number of medical exemptions in a school given its type and enrollment size. A hypothesis test is also ran to detemerine the odds of students claiming a religious exemption to vaccination increase or decrease with public school status.

Feature Engineering:

Create the following new variables:

  • public_dummy = Indicator variable that is 1 for public school 0 for private.
  • hi_enrollment = Indicator variable that is 1 when enrollment > mean enrollment.
  • relig_exempt = Indicator that is 1 when religious > 0, and 0 otherwise.

Developing a linear regression model:

  • Reseach Question: Can we develop a linear regression model to predict the number of medical exemptions in public and private schools based on school type and enrollment?
  • Develop a linear regression model that predicts medical exemptions (medical) ~ from public / private school (pubpriv) and enrollment.

Using Predictive Modeling Outputs to Enhance Decision-Making Solutions:

  • Linear Regression: Evaluating the Relationship Between Dependent and Independent Variables.

  • GOAL:

    • Minimize the error between the predicted and true values of the target variable.

Hypothesis Test Set-up

  • Ho:
    • There is no linear relationship and difference between the variables.
  • Ha:
    • There is a linear relationship and difference between the variables.

Discussioin of Hypothesis and p-values:

  • In the model summary, the Multiple R-squared value is 0.006469, and 0.6% represents the covariance in the dependent variable that is accounted for by the model, showing to have insignificant amount of discrimination between the predictors.
  • The Adjusted R-squared value is 0.002641 (0.2%), and 0.2% suggest that regardless of the sample size the performance of the prediction model is very weak.
    • The degrees of freedom attached to the model is 695 and the 3 observations removed are accounted for by 1 degree of freedom for the grand mean and 2 for the predictors utilized.
    • The F-value and its associated P-value is testing whether the R-squared value is significantly different from 0. For this analysis, the decision is to fail to reject the null hypothesis because the p-value is p-value: 0.1856 and is above the alpha threshold .05. There is a 18% probability that an observed difference between the observed results and expected results is due to chance or sampling error.
  • The T-test is used to model the statistical significance of individual coefficients and the P-value associated with this value displays the probability that the observed difference between the groups is due to chance. In exercise 3, the null hypothesis is that each estimate coefficient is equal to zero.
    • For the variable of public vs Private, the T-value is -1.807 and P-value is 0.0712, leading to the decision to fail to reject the null hypothesis because the P-value is greater than the alpha (0.05.)
    • For the environment variable, the T-value is 1.879 and P-value is 0.0607. Due to the P-value being greater than the threshold of P < .05, the decision is to fail to reject the null hypothesis.

A write up of the results from the logistic regression model, with an interpretation of the question:

  • how do the odds of students claiming a religious exemption to vaccination increase or decrease with public school status?.
    • Incorporate a discussion of hypothesis tests , p-values and odds ratios.

Hypothesis Test Set-up

  • Ho: There is no linear relationship and difference between the variables.
  • Ha: There is a linear relationship and difference between the variables.

Hypothesis Test and P-values

  • For both, enrollment size and public vs.private school variables the corresponding p-value on the F-stat on overall fit is large, meaning the regression is not fit as well as the associated z-scores.
    • enrollment:
      • z-value: 1.214
      • p = 0.225 == p>.05
    • public_dummy:
      • z-value: 0.395
      • p = 0.693 == p>.05
  • Referencing the outcome above, the decision is to fail to reject the null hypothesis,
    • which is the log-odds of enrollment size and the log-odds of public vs.private school variables is equal to 0 in the population.

Odds: odd ratio for coefficients:

  • The odds of 0.9583655:1 is the proportion for having a religious exemption by a person not enrolled in a school.
    • A person is about 4.2% for having a religious exemption to vaccination by a person not enrolled in a school.
  • Every increase of one in the enrollment size of a school is associated with a 1.0031110 to 1 increase in the odds of enrollment
    • For each student enrolled at a school, there is a 0.31% increase in the likelihood of a religious exemption to vaccination
      • Just about a 1 to 1 for each coefficient. Can be significant based on scale.
  • Every increase of one in public_dummy is associated with a 1.1177665 to 1 increase in the odds of relig_exempt.
    • A person is about 11% more likely to have a religious exemption to vaccination in a public school.

Deviance Residuals:

  • The deviance Residuals shows the distribution of residuals after the model is fit.
    • The mean of the residuals is very close to 0 and is a value of 0.04727531.
    • The median of the residuals is positive, 0.9886 and the histogram can be interpreted as including two separate distributions (binomial).
      • Breaking the distribution into two instances:
        • the left hand distribution is a negative skewed distribution of residuals.
        • The right hand side is also a negative skewed data frame. ### Odds: odd ratio for the 95% Confidence Interval:
  • The 95% confidence interval for public_dummy ranged from 0.6423183:1 up to 1.942758:1,
    • expressed in plain odds;
      • at the lower end (2.5%) there is a 35.7% increase in the likelihood of claiming to be religiously exempt from a vaccination when enrolled in a public school.
      • at the high end (97.5%) there is a 94.8% increase in the likelihood of claiming to be religiously exempt from a vaccination when enrolled in a public school.
  • if the study was repeated 100 times, 95% of similarly constructed intervals would contain the true population value.

By looking at p-values of the z statistic for both coeffients there is a strong likelihood that these observations occurring are due to chance.

  • For the variable enrollment size there is about a 23% probability that an observed difference between the observed results and expected results is due to chance or sampling error.
  • For the variable public pr private school There is a 69% probability that an observed difference between the observed results and expected results is due to chance or sampling error.

Overall, the conclusion drawn from the hypothesis test does not align with the conclusions drawn from the odds ratio.
